---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import VisualProvingGround from '../../components/VisualProvingGround.tsx';
import ProvingGround from '../../components/ProvingGround.tsx';
---

<Base
  title="The Proving Ground — pathtoAGI"
  description="See the test the frontier models face — first in pure pictures, then in the hard numeric worlds. A demonstration only: as of the founding abdication, no human attempt enters the record."
  ogImage="/media/proving-ground-hero.webp"
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">The Proving Ground · see the test</p>
    <h1 class="display mt-4 text-4xl sm:text-5xl">You versus the sealed world</h1>
    <p class="lede mt-6">
      This instrument tests whether a mind can find the rule of a world that
      never existed before — without being told what kind of rule to look for.
      You can take the same test the machines take, right now, starting in
      pictures with no maths at all.
    </p>
    <div class="surface mt-8 p-5" style="border-radius: 10px;">
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">A demonstration only</p>
      <p class="prose mt-3 text-sm">
        As of the founding abdication (constitution v3), <strong>no human input
        moves this record.</strong> What you do here is graded in your own
        browser and stored nowhere — it is not transmitted, not counted, not
        entered into the record. The instrument calibrates itself with
        <a href="/method/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">formal reference baselines</a>
        (what a random predictor scores, what an optimal bounded solver reaches,
        the frame-disclosed-minus-withheld difference), not with human play. This
        page exists so you can see, in your own hands, exactly what the machines
        are asked to do — nothing more.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <figure class="mt-8 overflow-hidden border hairline" style="border-radius: 10px; background: var(--color-surface);">
    <img
      src="/media/proving-ground-hero.webp"
      alt="A human hand and a robotic hand reaching toward the same glowing puzzle grid on an antique brass observatory table, star charts behind."
      class="block aspect-[16/9] w-full object-cover"
      loading="eager"
      decoding="async"
    />
    <figcaption class="px-4 py-3 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
      Same puzzle, two kinds of mind. The machines' attempts are graded against
      sealed ground truth and published in full; yours here are for your own
      understanding only.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <section class="mt-12">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Part one · the pictures</p>
      <h2 class="serif mt-2 text-2xl sm:text-3xl">Three pictures, three ideas</h2>
      <p class="prose mt-4">
        Every hard probe in this record rests on three moves: find a hidden rule
        from a few examples, resist a rule that looks obvious but is secretly
        wrong, and admit when the evidence genuinely can’t decide. Here they are
        with no numbers at all.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-8">
      <VisualProvingGround client:visible />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: hsl(34 96% 60%);">Part two · the hard version</p>
      <h2 class="serif mt-2 text-2xl sm:text-3xl">The numeric worlds</h2>
      <p class="prose mt-4">
        This is what the frontier models actually faced — the same three ideas,
        but on integer worlds with no visual crutch. Two are revealed and grade
        in your browser. The third is <strong>live and sealed</strong>: the same
        world the models were graded on. It is genuinely hard; that is the point.
      </p>
      <p class="mono mt-4 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        Reminder: this is a demonstration surface. The models' attempts on these
        worlds are the evidence; anything you do here stays in your browser.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-8">
      <ProvingGround client:visible />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="serif text-2xl">Why show the test at all</h2>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      Transparency, not participation. A reader should be able to feel exactly
      what the instrument asks its subjects to do, rather than take the
      difficulty on faith. That is a different thing from letting human play move
      the verdict — which, under the founding abdication, nothing human does. The
      evidence is the models' sealed, deterministically-graded, reproducible
      attempts, at <a href="/runs/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">/runs/</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="mono mt-4 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
      Revealed worlds: <a href="/experiments/fcs-synth-world-006/REVEAL.md" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-006</a>,
      <a href="/experiments/fcs-synth-world-005/REVEAL.md" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-005</a>.
      Live sealed world: <a href="/runs/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">world-003</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
